Brief Explanation of DFS Program

Depth First Search (DFS) is a graph traversal technique used to visit all vertices of a graph.
In this program, the graph is represented using a dictionary where each vertex stores its neighboring vertices.

The user enters the number of vertices and edges, then inputs the edges of the undirected graph. Since the graph is undirected, connections are added in both directions.

The dfs() function works recursively:

First, it marks the current vertex as visited.
Then it prints the vertex.
After that, it checks all neighboring vertices.
If a neighbor is not visited, the function calls itself for that neighbor.

This process continues until all reachable vertices are visited exactly once.
